description: Published by the UK wing of Panini Comics. Initially the series reprinted US Spider-Man Adventures stories, set in the Spider-Man: The Animated Series cartoon universe. When available reprints ran out, the series switched to using brand new stories written and drawn by British creative teams, and shortly afterwards, with issue 70, the series dropped the word Adventures from its title. In late 2011, following new instructions from Marvel's US offices that original Marvel material was no longer to be produced outside the US, Spectacular Spider-Man switched to reprinting Spider-Man stories from the American Marvel Adventures imprint. This prompted a name change to Spider-Man Magazine, before changing again to Ultimate Spider-Man Magazine when it started printing material from the Ultimate Spider-Man TV tie-in comic.
name: Spectacular Spider-Man Adventures

description:
Created by Bosnian publisher and printer Ivo Milicevic, Strip Magazine is a British action-adventure comics anthology from Print Media Productions.

Launched in October 2011 (following the success of the free issue zero earlier that year), the title has seen a bumpy publishing history with a lengthy gap after issue four and the publication of a joint issue 5/6 many months later. With a planned 'volume two' not materialising in 2012, a belated Christmas special (issue 7) was published in December of that year.

Creators involved include a mix of British and European talent, including John McCrea, PJ Holden, John Ridgway, Ramon Sola, Paul Gastine, Jerome Felix and many others.
name: Strip Magazine

deck: Over a decade after Terminal, the residents of San Francisco live a peaceful and prosperous existence thanks to the Program. Every resident of the city is hand-selected and implanted with the chip Secura, which removes the human capacity for violence to maintain the greater good. Only the city's security forces are allowed a brief reprieve from Secura through use of the drug Freestone in order to do their jobs. Now, rumors of Freestone getting out into the open market threaten to upset the delicate balance

description:
Volume 1.

1986 saw the debut of the horror anthology Gore Shriek, edited by Stephen R. Bissette, who also contributed stories to each issue. Besides Bissette, other Gore Shriek creators of note included Greg Capullo, Bruce Spaulding Fuller, Eric Stanway and Gurchain Singh. Gore Shriek volume I ran for three years (1986 - '89), and is still fondly remembered by horror fans as one of the top comics in that genre. (Wikipedia)

See: Volume 2 (1990-91), and the Gore Shriek Annual (1990).
name: Gore Shriek
